metadata.name: Mosaic #204
metadata.description:
---
Notes:
- Click to pause/unpause
- The aspect ratio is fixed 1:1 because of the way the grid and movements are generated to make sure they're the same on all screens. 
---
Description:
An 80X80 grid of tiles are scrambled, shuffled, shifted, streamed, transported,
conveyed, moved, deposited. 

There are 15 initial tile states and 5 color palettes. A set of 12 unique motion patterns
are generated for each piece. 
---
Acknowledgements:
This piece is inspired by Kim Asendorf, whose pixel-level algorithms I'm
transfixed by, and Ksawery Komputery, whose algorithmic tile-works I'm crazy
about. 
---
Made by Sam Tsao (@sam___tsao) with P5.js 
December 2021, Germany

metadata.name: Waves and Ripples #111
metadata.description:
Waves and Ripples is an implementation of a continuous CA, where wave like behaviours are obtained from the influence of neighbour cells over the cell itself. Depeding on the connections config for each cell, different patterns will emerge, creating waves, ripples, or a mix of both. When single loop is on, the calculations and drawings are done at once, which makes for a more chaotic visual.
Best enjoyed in full-screen :) 

Click anywhere to restart

Features : 
  shrinkFactor : 3 types
  connectArray: 16 possibilities,
  extraConnection: 4 types,
  mutualNeighbour: 40% chance,
  singleLoop: 30% chance
  monoChromo:  15% chance

Inspired by Matt Pearson's book.

metadata.name: Reading a book #602
metadata.description:
The formal structure of a book is beautiful by itself, but its aesthetic is the tacit atmosphere within which events take place in a story.

The WebGL real-time animation sets up an initial grid based on the fxhash. The grid cells get subdivided into another grid and the resulting cells become filled with pixels in color (~33%) or black and white (~66%).
The colored pixels come in 3 different coloring styles.
- Big Palette (~49%)
- Small Palette (~49%)
- Monochrome [b/w] (~2%)
4 noise algorithms modify the pixels of selected grid cells while at the same time 4 reset algorithms reassemble the initial image. The selected cells switch over time.

metadata.name: Orchard #355
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit.

metadata.name: Meander River Plot v1 #97
metadata.description:
A river meandering over a noise-based landscape. A line is drawn either horizontally, vertically, or more rarely, a ring. Time progresses for 1,000 iterations as the line travels, bends, and splits. 

There is a lot of variation on the line quality - from thin and controlled, to chunky and chaotic. It's a lot of fun to watch it run and see where it ends up.

I've been experimenting with this algorithm for a long time and this is the most visually interesting variation so far.

metadata.name: Action Fields #346
metadata.description:
A generative painting based on abstract expressionism and the action paintings of Jackson Pollock.

Several different flow fields are used to create paths which are then painted in one of four different styles (pastel, paint, Pollock, black+gold). Additional features affect the background, path length + angles, level of detail, and mess (drips and splats). 

NOTES: 
- Some variations of the Pollock style may appear slightly different between browsers, but will render consistently in the same browser. 
- On slower devices, it may take some time to being drawing due to the background rendering.
- If you get a browser warning that the page is taking a long time, press continue.

Viewing in desktop Chrome is recommended for the best results.
Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 1200x928px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

Add '&size=#' to the end of the live view URL to render a variation of your edition at a resolution from 300 to 5,000 px. The ideal higher resolution is 2,000px.
